Anonymous Thu 20 Dec 2018 00:02:07 No.20128596 Report

>>20127564
Oliver_Hart here. I use the setting that anthros and humans have "grown up" alongside each other, leading to a somewhat mixed society, unless otherwise specified. I've always thought that writing furry stuff is a waste if you don't address the fact that the other person is a literal animal with human-like intelligence or greater. Hence why I incorporate things like Scent Masks, Estrus Blockers, racial advantages and disadvantages, etc. Also some kind of tension between different anthro groups, or between humans and anthros. Things aren't always peachy, though you can choose to soften or harden the relations between the different groups as you please. So for example, Liquid Courage takes place in an environment where there is a lot of tension between humans and anthros.

The Pits takes place in such a world as well, except that predators and prey animals are heavily divided. Same with STALKER, as there is a caste system among canid predators. LoF, Beating the Heat and If A Bear is Hungry have softer tensions.

I do my fair share of worldbuilding, but try to keep that from overwhelming the story.

In my very first attempts at writing, even before being aware of the furry fandom i've wrote a story about alien contact where the humans where the aliens. At first things were peaceful until the humans finished making all preparations to bring another fleet stationed just outside the reach of the planetary defenses/detection technology.

War erupted but the anthros were at total disadvantage in tech, even species, or variants as i called back then, with stronger builds could be subdued by groups of enhanced humans in hand to hand combat.

The first skirmishes where mostly melee because the humans barely had energy sources to power their weapons, and the planet didn't reached nuclear technology yet, nor the humans would share such knowledge as it could be used against as well as make whole regions of the planet unfit for colonization.

Humans had numbers anyway. And there was a resistance among the humans, but only a few of them had been enhanced for combat and the whole plot was around how a group making contact/saving a platton of anthros.

Hey! Happy to see someone else interested in taking a crack at a story. It's always great to see another author on here. On the good front, your grammar seems passable, and it sounds like you've got a decent amount of thought put into the world you want to show us. What's more, I like that there's some thought into the history of the MC. That'll give you a huge leg up in making him a full, three dimensional, character with strengths, weaknesses, prejudices, and blind spots.

If you're looking for some creative feedback, I do have a couple of things to add. Don't take this as ripping on your writing, so much as opportunities to grow as a writer:

- As >>20135605 has mentioned, the use of forced second person is a tricky thing to pull off. It pays dividends when you're looking to write a fap-fic or create a juxtaposition when writing from multiple perspectives. That said, I would also recommend you go 3rd person past tense if you want to continue this story.

- As you mentioned, this preamble is extremely brief, and perhaps as a consequence of that, it reads like something between a news report and a character ref. sheet for a D&D campaign. If that's what this is, then rockin', but if you want people to get immersed / invested, you're better served by focusing on "Show, don't tell" writing. You can find pretty good examples of this in Hobo's stuff, Jacklin's stuff, or Bed-Man's stuff. Swear off the Crime Novels for a while, if you read them. They tend to create bad habits.

- Last but not least, there's your sentence structure. I realize that I'm leaping headfirst into hypocritical territory, but I'd recommend you try to break up / streamline / simplify your sentences a bit. I wouldn't worry too much about this, as it's something that generally sorts itself out with continued writing. You'll get a feel for what reads well and what gets wordy.

Looking forward to seeing how your gimpy judge and one eye'd rogue meet and fall for each other!
